This is interesting! Look at lines 299-314:

```java
// if passed tag has an assigned endpoint, return it and be done
if (!TextUtils.isEmpty(tag.getEndpoint())) {
    return getRelativeEndpoint(tag.getEndpoint());
}

// check the db for the endpoint
String endpoint = ReaderTagTable.getEndpointForTag(tag);
if (!TextUtils.isEmpty(endpoint)) {
    return getRelativeEndpoint(endpoint);
}

// never hand craft the endpoint for default tags, since these MUST be updated
// using their stored endpoints
if (tag.tagType == ReaderTagType.DEFAULT) {
    return null;
}
return formatRelativeEndpointForTag(tag.getTagSlug());
```

This is KEY! The logic is:
1. If the tag has an endpoint, use it
2. If the tag is in the DB, get its endpoint from there
3. If it's a DEFAULT tag type without an endpoint, return null (which likely causes an error or no-op)
4. Otherwise, build the endpoint from the tag slug

The problem: When we create a tag with `ReaderTagType.FOLLOWED`, if that tag isn't in the database (because it's NOT actually followed), it will try to get the endpoint from the database (line 304). If that fails (which it will because the tag isn't followed), it will then check if the tagType is DEFAULT. Since our tag type is FOLLOWED (not DEFAULT), it will proceed to line 314 and build the endpoint using `formatRelativeEndpointForTag`.

So it SHOULD work...but wait, let me check the `ReaderTagTable.getEndpointForTag` method to see if it behaves differently for FOLLOWED tags:

